03905nam a22005895i 9780226983660DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082007ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802269836607 a10.7208/97802269836602doi  a(DE-B1597)523815  a(OCoLC)1058736163  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBL98.7 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a306.6a306.6a809.93382041 aZiolkowski, Theodore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModes of Faith :bSecular Surrogates for Lost Religious Belief /cTheodore Ziolkowski. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart One: The Decline of Faith -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Melancholy, Long, Withdrawing Roar -- t3. Theologians of the Profane -- tPart Two: New Modes of Faith -- t4. The Religion of Art -- t5. Pilgrimages to India -- t6. The God That Failed -- t7. The Hunger for Myth -- t8. The Longing for Utopia -- tPart Three: Conclusion -- t9. Renewals of Spirituality -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the decades surrounding World War I, religious belief receded in the face of radical new ideas such as Marxism, modern science, Nietzschean philosophy, and critical theology. Modes of Faith addresses both this decline of religious belief and the new modes of secular faith that took religion’s place in the minds of many writers and poets. Theodore Ziolkowski here examines the motives for this embrace of the secular, locating new modes of faith in art, escapist travel, socialism, politicized myth, and utopian visions. James Joyce, he reveals, turned to art as an escape while Hermann Hesse made a pilgrimage to India in search of enlightenment. Other writers, such as Roger Martin du Gard and Thomas Mann, sought temporary solace in communism or myth. And H. G. Wells, Ziolkowski argues, took refuge in utopian dreams projected in another dimension altogether. Rooted in innovative and careful comparative reading of the work of writers from France, England, Germany, Italy, and Russia, Modes of Faith is a critical masterpiece by a distinguished literary scholar that offers an abundance of insight to anyone interested in the human compulsion to believe in forces that transcend the individual.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEuropean literature. 0aImplicit religion. 0aLiterature. 0aReligion and literature. 0aReligion. 0aSecularism in literature. 0aSecularism. 0aSocial sciences. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aZiolkowski, Theodore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226983660423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226983660.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles